!!!
%html.no-js{:lang => "en"}
  %head
    %title Gulp 4 Boilerplate - Perforations and Dividers
    %meta{:content => "ie=edge", "http-equiv" => "x-ua-compatible"}/
    %meta{:content => "width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0", :name => "viewport"}/
    %link{:href => "../assets/css/sard-styles.min.css", :rel => "stylesheet"}/
 
  %body
    //=include ../navbars/_navbar-x1.haml

    .container
      .row
        .col-sm-12
          %h1#links.bs-anchor Perforations and Dividers
          %p Throughout SARD we use a variety of perforations and divders to visually seperate sections.

      .row
        .col-sm-12
          %h3 Horizontal Rules
          %p We have created a range of HR thickness and colours.
          %h5 A standard HR 
          %code hr 
          %hr/
          %h5 Various weights
          %p Add the weights as below. 
          %code hr.x2 
          %hr.x2/
          %code hr.x4 
          %hr.x4/
          %code hr.x8 
          %hr.x8/
          %code hr.x12 
          %hr.x12/
          %code hr.x16 
          %hr.x16/

          %h5 Various colours
          %p Add the colours as below. 
          %code hr.black 
          %hr.black/
          %code hr.primary 
          or 
          %code hr.client
          %hr.primary/
          %code hr.secondary 
          or 
          %code hr.admin
          %hr.secondary/
          %code hr.white
          .card.card-sard
            .card-body
              %hr.white/
          
          %h5 Various styles
          %code hr.dashed 
          %hr.dashed/
          %code hr.dotted 
          %hr.dotted/
          
          %h5 Mix n match
          %code hr.client.dashed.x4
          %hr.client.dashed.x4/
          %code hr.admin.dotted.x12
          %hr.admin.x12.dotted

          

      .row
        .col-sm-12
          %h3.mt-3 Perforations 
          %p Dotted horizontal rules don't always behave well in varions browsers, So we have created a set of perforations that can be used as dividers instead.

          %p
            %code .perf.client
            .perf.client
          %h5 Various weights
          %p
            %code .perf.client.x2
            .perf.client.x2
          %p
            %code .perf.client.x4
            .perf.client.x4
          %p
            %code .perf.client.x8
            .perf.client.x8
          %p
            %code .perf.client.x12
            .perf.client.x12
          %p
            %code .perf.client.x16
            .perf.client.x16

          %h5 Various colours
          %p
            %code .perf.black
            .perf.black.x8 
          %p
            %code .perf.primary
            or
            %code .perf.client
            .perf.client.x8
          %p
            %code .perf.secondary
            or
            %code .perf.admin
            .perf.secondary.x8
          %p
            %code .perf.white
          .card.card-sard 
            .card-body
              .perf.white.x8
            
      .row
        .col-sm-12
          %h3.mt-3 Perforations as Card dividers
          %p Perforations were origionally designed as dividers between card body dividers. They can be placed within Cards, Panels or Fieldsets to divide them.

        .col-sm-4 
          .card.card-sard 
            .card-header Card
            .card-body
              %p 
                They can be placed between two card bodies
            .perf
            .card-body
              %p Like this
              %hr.black/
              %p Or within a .card-body 
              .perf
              %p like this
          %p
            The Default Perforation for use in Cards is white, 8px. So you only need to have the following code:
            %br/
            %code .card-body
            %br/
            %code .perf
            %br/
            %code .card-body

        .col-sm-4 
          .panel.panel-sard 
            .panel-header Panel
            .panel-body
              %p 
                They can be placed between two panel bodies
            .perf
            .panel-body
              %p  Like this
              %hr.black/
              %p Or within a .panel-body 
              .perf
              %p like this
          %p
            The Default Perforation for use in panels is white, 8px. So you only need to have the following code:
            %br/
            %code .panel-body
            %br/
            %code .perf
            %br/
            %code .panel-body

        .col-sm-4 
          %fieldset 
            %legend Fieldset
            .form-group
              %p 
                They can be placed between two form groups
            .perf
            .form-group
              %p  Like this
              %hr.black/
              %p Or within a .form-group 
              .perf
              %p like this
          %p
            The Default Perforation for use in fieldsets is white, 8px. So you only need to have the following code:
            %br/
            %code .form-group
            %br/
            %code .perf
            %br/
            %code .form-group
      .row
        .col-sm-12
          %h1#links.bs-anchor Links

      .row
        .col-sm-12
          %p
            This is an example of a standard
            %a{href: "#/"} Text Link

      %hr

      .row
        .col-sm-12
          %h4 Links in Cards, Panels and Fieldsets

        .col-sm-4
          %h5 Links in Cards
          .card.card-sard
            .card-header 
              %a{href: "#/"} Link in Card Header
            .card-body
              %h5.card-title 
                %a{href: "#/"} Link in Card Title
              %p.card-text 
                Standard
                %a{href: "#/"} Link in Card Text
              %p 
                %a{href: "#/"} Link in Card Body
            .card-footer
              %a{href: "#/"} Link in Card Footer


        .col-sm-4
          %h5 Links in Panels
          .panel.card-sard
            .panel-header 
              %a{href: "#/"} Link in Panel Header
            .panel-body
              %h5.panel-title 
                %a{href: "#/"} Link in Panel Title
              %p.panel-text 
                Standard
                %a{href: "#/"} Link in Panel Text
              %p 
                %a{href: "#/"} Link in Panel Body
            .panel-footer
              %a{href: "#/"} Link in Panel Footer


        .col-sm-4 
          %h5 Links in Fieldsets 
          %fieldset.fieldset-sard
            %legend 
              Standard
              %a{href: "#/"} Link in Legend
            .form-group
              %label
                %a{href: "#/"} Link in Label
              %br/
              %p
                Standard
                %a{href: "#/"} Link in Form Group
            .form-footer
              Standard
              %a{href: "#/"} Link in Footer

        .col-sm-12
          .card.card-sard
            .card-header 
              Links with specific icons
            .card-body.border-bottom
              %p
                Link icons can be place directly onto the link, or on the containing paragraph or span. They should have the class of .link-icon
                and either .link-NAME or .NAME . i.e 
                %code .link-icon.link-pdf
                or
                %code .link-icon.pdf
                \. They are designed so that the text of the link hangs from the icon.
              
            -# Examples
            .card-body.pb-0
              %h6.base Examples
            .card-body.multi-column-3-white
              %a.link-icon.link-pdf{href: "#/"} 
                %span.text-default Direct 
                %code (a.link-icon.link-pdf) 
                %span.text-default Link to pdf, this a really, really long title so it wraps onto the next line.
              
              %a.link-icon.pdf{href: "#/"}
                %span.text-default Direct 
                %code (a.link-icon.pdf) 
                %span.text-default Link to pdf, this a really, really long title so it wraps onto the next line.
              
              %p.link-icon.link-pdf
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  %span.text-default Link within a paragraph 
                  %code (p.link-icon.link-pdf)
                  %span.text-default ,  Some long title
              
              %p.link-icon.pdf
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  %span.text-default Link within a paragraph 
                  %code (p.link-icon.pdf)
                  %span.text-default , Some long title, so it wraps around to show the indent.

              %span.link-icon.link-pdf
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  %span.text-default Link within a span 
                  %code (span.link-icon.link-pdf)
                  %span.text-default , Some long title, so it wraps around to show the indent.

              %span.link-icon.pdf
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  %span.text-default Link within a span 
                  %code (span.link-icon.pdf)
                  %span.text-default , Some long title, so it wraps around to show the indent.

            -# File Types
            .card-body.pb-0.border-top
              %h6.base File Types
              %p You can use any of the file extensions within the brackets ( ).
            .card-body.multi-column-3-white
              %p.link-icon.audio
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  AUDIO 
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-audio
                or
                %code .link-icon.audio
             
              %p.link-icon.xls
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  EXCEL (xls, xlsx)
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-xls
                or
                %code .link-icon.xls

              %p.link-icon.image
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  IMAGES (gif, ico, image, jpg, photo, png )
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-image
                or
                %code .link-icon.image

              %p.link-icon.pdf
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  PDF
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-pdf
                or
                %code .link-icon.pdf

              %p.link-icon.ppt
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  POWERPOINT (ppt, pptm, pptx)
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-ppt
                or
                %code .link-icon.ppt

              %p.link-icon.txt
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  TEXT (txt, odt, rtf)
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-txt
                or
                %code .link-icon.txt

              %p.link-icon.video
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  VIDEO
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-video
                or
                %code .link-icon.video

              %p.link-icon.doc
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  WORD (doc, docm, docx)
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-doc
                or
                %code .link-icon.doc

              %p.link-icon.zip
                %a{href: "#/"} 
                  ZIP (zip, archive)
                  %br
                %code .link-icon.link-zip
                or
                %code .link-icon.zip

        .col-sm-12
          .card.card-sard
            .card-header 
              Links icons within a table
            .card-body
              %table.table.table-sard.table-bordered
                %thead
                  %tr
                    %th th
                    %th th
                %tbody
                  %tr
                    %td 
                      %a.link-icon.link-pdf{href: "#/"} 
                        %code a.link-icon.link-pdf 
                        %span.text-default within a td with no class added. 
                        %br
                        %span.text-default Really, long, long title to exdent it to a new line.

                    %td.link-icon
                      %a.link-pdf{href: "#/"} 
                        %span.text-default Link 
                        %code (a.link-pdf)
                        %span.text-default within a td with the class of 
                        %code (td.link-icon)
                        %br
                        %span.text-default Some long title, so it wraps around to show the indent.
                      
                      %a.link-pdf{href: "#/"} 
                        %span.text-default Another Link 
                        %code (a.link-pdf)
                        %span.text-default within the same td with the class of 
                        %code (td.link-icon)
                        %br
                        %span.text-default Some long title, so it wraps around to show the indent.



              
              


